comments: I thought this was difficult and possibly subjective? I'd be curious to know what the researchers had in mind and what the "correct" answers were. I felt like I was trying to apply some kind of logic or reasoning to determine the answers and sometimes wondered if I was over  thinking it or if I was right!
The meaning of some of these statements would depend highly on the context of the situation and the things said before and after them.
Interesting exercise and something I don't typically think about.

Had to think about my responses because the questions were ambiguous. In most cases, the person did answer the question as to whether or not something was done, but not as to whether the 3rd person said or did something.

This was interesting to think about. I'm not really sure what I think about some of them; it seems like there needs to be more explanation on the part of the speakers to clarify their statements and questions.
Nothing that I can think of, thank you.
It was interesting. Thank you for the opportunity.
a bit tedious, but ultimately interesting.
I wonder how many people begin their sentences with 'Perhaps' when they're talking about another person's knowledge.
None. I find it interesting and would love to participate in future studies
I feel like most of the answers to the questions were all the same.
Very interesting survey! Tricky wording. I'm currently trying to teach a native Arabic speaker English, and these are great examples of why it is so hard! Be well.
The scale of certainty was a little confusing.

Those were weird statements that no one would ever make so it was a little tricky.  Also, when the askers asked "Are you sure?" we don't know what they were asking because they weren't clear/explicit.  So that's why I marked a bunch of them right down the middle.
The questions are tricky because they might've answered one part of the question but not the other to confirm if the person that suggested or said something actually did it....interesting
the intentions of reading these statements depend on your understand of what "perhaps" means

I noticed that in the first set of questions, the second speaker COULD be responding to the second part of the first speaker's sentence, so it is possible that the first speaker's answer IS answering the "are you sure" question.
none. this was a bit challenging
It took me a while to get the feel for what the questions were asking so my first answers in each section aren't as solid as the later answers

It was difficult for me sometimes to determine the level of certainty on the part of the speaker. In my experience, tone and intonation are very important in determining someone's meaning. Some instances were very clear, when the speaker stated something that was happening as a fact (e.g., the kids are in the garage) but others were a little more unclear. I tried to make my decision based off how speculative the speaker sounded, like if they were guessing about what actually happened or merely expressing an opinion.
I thought for most of the questions I could be a maybe no based on how the dialogue was set up.

I found this quite difficult without hearing the context of the sentences. I feel like if I had heard these questions spoke out loud I would have known for sure but just reading them it was hard to decipher if the question was answered

This was interesting and a little tricky. Sometimes the wording was a little off, making the sentence ambiguous. I just want to make sure that my responses don't look random!
In any event, I appreciated participating and wish you well with your research.
I was a little confused in the first half of the study. "Perhaps" implies uncertainty so I didn't think the people were entirely positive about their responses.
I would be interested to see the result.
This was hard to understand at first even after reading the initial instructions. I am sure I got several of the first questions wrong in both of the two sets.
No offense, but a little repetitive especially at the beginning.

I think that the first section was generally a "no" for most answers as the possible fact was being restated, but the action around that fact was still uncertain, so the question was never truly answered.
What was the question? How do I know if they answered the question if the question isn't there.
I was a bit confused at first, but after the first few questions, I understood it.
Hardly anyone talks like 'perhaps x established that y', it's needlessly complicated.
